Hemorrhagic septicemia, cattle - Malaysia (Terengganu) 19991216.2171
Date: 17 Jul 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters, 17 Jul 2001 [edited


Malaysian state fights deadly cow disease
-----------------------------------------
KUALA LUMPUR - Malaysian workers are racing to vaccinate 17 000 cows and
buffalo against an infectious disease that has killed 47 animals in the
northeast of the country.

Officials have declared an epidemic of hemorrhagic septicemia in one
district of Kelantan state bordering Thailand. The state's director of
veterinary services, Idris Kadir, hopes vaccinations will prevent the
disease from spreading.

The bacterial disease, which can be spread by direct contact and
contaminated food or water, is one of the most serious to hit cows and
buffalo in southeast Asia and can kill infected beasts within 6 hours.

Symptoms include high fever, bleeding eyes, running nose, swollen joints
and diarrhea.

Humans are not affected. [Actually, wound infections of humans are not
uncommon, and may progress to cellulitis and/or osteomyelitis. The bites
of small animals are a common means of human exposure. - Mod.ES

Kelantan has banned movement of the animals in and out of the district,
Rantau Panjang.

Farmers say their losses total 150 000 ringgit (39 480 US dollars).

In 2000, the northeast state vaccinated 16 800 cattle after the disease
surfaced there and in neighboring Terengganu.

In March, Terengganu said it was vaccinating 90 000 cattle after the
disease killed 240 animals there.
--
