<promed@promedmail.org>
[Hemorrhagic septicemia is an acute pasteurellosis, caused by particular
serotypes of _Pasteurella multocida_ and manifest by an acute and highly
fatal septicemia, generally in cattle and water buffalo. Water buffalo are
thought to be more susceptible than cattle, and the disease occurs
infrequently in swine and is even more rarely in sheep and goats. However,
it has been reported in bison, camels, elephants, horses and donkeys, and
there is evidence it occurs in the yak.
Infection usually occurs by direct or indirect contact. The source of
infective bacteria is thought to be the nasopharynx of bovine or buffalo
carriers. As many as 5 percent of these animals may be carriers in
endemic areas.

In susceptible animals, a septicemia develops rapidly, and death due to
endotoxemia ensues within 8-24 hours after the first signs.
The mortality rate is high when the agent is introduced to non endemic
regions. Losses vary widely in endemic areas. The heaviest losses occur
during the monsoon rains in southeast Asia, and it is thought the
organism survives for hours, probably days in moist soil and water.
Because the course of the disease is so short, clinical signs may be
overlooked. The first evidence is dullness, a reluctance to move, fever,
salivation and serous nasal discharge. Edematous swelling is frequently
seen, beginning in the throat region and spreading to the parotid region,
neck and brisket. Mucous membranes are congested and there is respiratory
distress. The animal usually goes down. Recovery is rare and there is no
chronic form.
Characteristic epidemiologic and clinical features aid in the recognition
of this disease. Sporadic cases may be difficult to diagnose clinically,
particularly in endemic areas. Differentials include anthrax, acute
salmonellosis, pneumonic pasteurellosis and rinderpest.
Presumptive diagnosis is based on the isolation of _P. multocida_ from
the blood and vital organs. The causative agent may be overgrown and
obscured by extraneous bacteria if there is postmortem decomposition.
The principle means of prevention is by vaccination. Three kinds include
the plain bacterin, alum-type precipitated bacterin, and oil-adjuvant
bacterin. The most effective is the oil-adjuvant, providing 9-12 months
of protection for one injection.
Because the course of the disease is so rapid treatment is difficult.
However various sulfonamides, tetracyclines, and penicillin are effective
when administered early. - Mod.TG
